properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Lower Assiniboine River
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Assiniboine River from the Souris River to the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-20T13:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-19T13:59:07-05:00, 6A25EEC9-6536-96FF-925E-9C509D2944B1
Area: Assiniboine River from the Souris River to the City of Winnipeg
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Traffic Hazard Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: Yellowhead County fire crews currently working on a collision involving a semi on Hwy 32 north of Twp Rd 570. It is a HAZMAT situation with a required radius of 150 feet from the spill. Their is no through access for the protection of crews onsite as well as for passing motorists. There are no detours on county roads. Alternative routes must be taken for those traveling North/South. ### Go to www.511.alberta.ca for up to date Road Report information.
Expires: 2019-10-26T09:48:09-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Yellowhead County, 2019-10-19T09:46:23-06:00, NAADS-CA-AB-AEA1-6071
Area: Yellowhead County

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking out of the northern Prairie provinces has spread wet snow mixed at times with rain into Whale Cove, Rankin Inlet, and Chesterfield Inlet today. Accumulations will likely be in the 2 to 4 cm range and will be limited somewhat by melting and compaction. The snow also continues in Naujaat today, and will continue to be heavier through today, tonight and even into Sunday. The snow may start to mix with rain overnight or on Sunday after which time further accumulations will be limited. Total snowfall accumulations at Naujaat this weekend will likely end up in the 20 to 30 cm range. In addition to the snow, strong southeast winds will gust to 60 or 70 km/h, creating blowing snow at times. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-20T00:44:30-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-19T08:45:30-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0378846475.2019
Area: Naujaat
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions today and tonight. The winds will gradually ease on Sunday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-20T06:01:05-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-19T14:02:05-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4257032512.2019
Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant coastal rain and high-elevation snow continues. Additional rainfall: 40 mm near Natuashish and 10 to 15 mm near Nain. Additional snowfall: Near 5 cm inland and over higher terrain. Timespan: continuing until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rain, at times heavy, will continue along the north coast of Labrador through Sunday. Over the higher elevations inland, precipitation will continue to fall as snow tonight, however accumulations will be more modest. Precipitation will taper to showers on Sunday morning near Nain and by Sunday evening over remaining areas. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for possible winter conditions at higher elevations. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-20T10:59:38-00:00
